{"title_page": "Saint Paul Union Depot", "text_new": "{{other uses|Spud (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox station\n | style                      = Amtrak\n | name                       = Union Depot\n | image                      = {{Photomontage|photo1a=Saint Paul Union Depot - headhouse panorama - 2015-07-26.jpg|photo2a=Saint Paul Union Depot - waiting room - 2015-07-26.jpg|photo2b=Saint Paul Union Depot - concourse - 2015-07-26.jpg|photo3a=Saint Paul Union Depot at Christmastime 18.jpg|photo3b=Saint Paul Union Depot Ticket Station.jpg|position=center|spacing=1|border=0|color=white|color_border=white|size= 270|foot_montage=Left to right from top:facade of the head house, waiting room, concourse, inside of the headhouse, Entrance from lower parking ramp with ticket stations for Jefferson Lines and Amtrak}}\n | address                    = 214 Fourth Street East<br />[[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], [[Minnesota]] 55101\n | country                    = United States\n | coordinates                = {{coord|44|56|52|N|93|5|10|W|format=dms|region:US-MN_scale:10000_type:railwaystation|display=inline}}\n | map_type                   = USA Minnesota#USA\n | map_caption                = Location in Minnesota##Location in United States\n | website                    = http://www.uniondepot.org/\n | platform                   = 9 historically<br/>3 currently\n | tracks                     = 18 historically<br/>2 currently\n | bus_stands                 = 6\n | bus_operators              = {{bus icon|12px}} [[Metro Transit (Minnesota)|Metro Transit]]<br/>{{bus icon|12px}} [[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority|MVTA]]<br/>{{bus icon|12px}} [[Jefferson Lines]]<br/>{{bus icon|12px}} [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]]<br/>{{bus icon|12px}} [[Megabus (North America)|Megabus]]\n | bus_routes                 = {{bus icon|12px}} [[Metro Transit (Minnesota)|Metro Transit]]: 3, 16, 21, 54, 63, 70, 94, 262, 350, 351, 361, 364, 417<br/>{{bus icon|12px}} [[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority|MVTA]]: 480, 484, 489\n | parking                    = 12 short-term and 1000 long-term parking spaces\n | bicycle                    = Yes\n | opened                     = Original depot: 1881<br/>Current structure built 1917\u20131923\n | rebuilt                    = 2011\n | former                     = \n | passengers                 = 96,539<ref>{{cite web |title= Amtrak Fact Sheet, FY2016, State of Minnesota|publisher= [[Amtrak]] |date= November 2016 |url= https://www.amtrak.com/ccurl/219/46/MINNESOTA16.pdf |format= PDF |accessdate= 2017-02-20}}</ref>\n | pass_year                  = 2016\n | pass_percent               = 4.8\n | pass_system                = Amtrak\n | line                       = [[Canadian Pacific Railway]] [[Merriam Park Subdivision]]\n | ADA                        = Yes\n | code                       = MSP\n | owned                      = [[Ramsey County, Minnesota|Ramsey County Regional Railroad Authority]]\n | operator                   = [[Jones Lang LaSalle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.regionalrail.org/?p=1223|title=Contract with Jones Lang LaSalle for services at Union Depot approved|work=Ramsey County Regional Rail News|publisher=Ramsey County Regional Rail Authority|date=July 25, 2012|access-date=December 6, 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330031423/http://blog.regionalrail.org/?p=1223|archive-date=March 30, 2013|df=}}</ref>\n | zone                       = \n | services                   = {{Adjacent stations|system1=Amtrak\n|line1=Empire Builder|left1=St. Cloud|right1=Red Wing\n|system2=Metro (Minnesota)\n|line2=Green Line|left2=Central}}\n | other_services_header      = Former services\n | other_services_collapsible = yes\n | other_services             = {{Adjacent stations|system1=Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad|line1=Minneapolis-Chicago|left1=Minneapolis|right1=Prescott\n|system2=Chicago, Rock Island and Pacific Railroad|line2=Minneapolis-Houston|left2=Minneapolis|right2=Rosemount\n|line3=Minneapolis-Burlington|left3=Minneapolis|right3=Rosemount\n|system4=Chicago and North Western Railway|line4=Chicago-Minneapolis via Milwaukee|left4=Minneapolis|right4=Lake Elmo\n|line5=Chicago-Minneapolis via Madison|left5=Minneapolis|right5=Lake Elmo\n|line6=Minneapolis-Ashland|left6=Minneapolis|right6=Lake Elmo\n|line7=Omaha-Minneapolis|left7=Mendota, MN|right7=Minneapolis\n|system8=Milwaukee Road|line8=main|left8=Minnesota Transfer|right8=Langdon}}\n | nrhp                       =\n{{Infobox NRHP\n | name                 = Union Depot\n | nrhp_type            = indcp\n | nocat                = yes\n | partof               = [[Lowertown Historic District (Saint Paul, Minnesota)|Lowertown Historic District]]\n | partof_refnum        = 83000935\n | embed                = yes\n | image                = \n | caption              = \n | location             = 214 Fourth Street East<br/>[[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], [[Minnesota]]\n | coordinates          = {{coord|44|56|52|N|93|5|10|W|display=inline,title}}\n | area                 = \n | built                = 1917\n | architect            = Charles S. Frost\n | architecture         = Classical Revival\n | added                = December 18, 1974\n | designated_nrhp_type = February 21, 1983\n | refnum               = 74001040<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2006a}}</ref>\n}}<!-- this closes Infobox nrhp -->\n}}<!-- this closes Infobox station -->\nSaint Paul's '''Union Depot''' is a historic [[railroad station]] and [[intermodal passenger transport|intermodal]] transit hub in the Lowertown neighborhood of the city of [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]], [[Minnesota]], United States. It serves light rail, intercity rail, intercity bus, and local bus services.\n\nIt is the eastern terminus for the [[METRO Green Line]] light rail line, with the stop located outside the station's [[headhouse]]. It is also the [[Minneapolis\u2013St. Paul|Twin Cities]]' stop for [[Amtrak]], the national intercity railroad service. In addition to rail, Union Depot also serves [[Metro Transit (Minnesota)|Metro Transit]], [[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority|MVTA]], [[Jefferson Lines]], [[Greyhound Lines|Greyhound]], and [[Megabus (North America)|MegaBus]].\n\nThe headhouse, located at the 4th Street entrance, was designed by architect [[Charles Sumner Frost]] and is [[neoclassicism|neoclassical]] in style. The [[concourse]] and the waiting room that extend over the tracks are viewed as a great architectural achievements. The building was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1974. It is also a [[contributing property]] to the [[Lowertown Historic District (Saint Paul, Minnesota)|Lowertown Historic District]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lowertown Historic District|url=http://nrhp.mnhs.org/DistrictProperties.cfm?NPSNum=83000935|work=Minnesota National Register Properties Database|publisher=[[Minnesota Historical Society]]|year=2009|accessdate=January 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to its transit uses, Union Depot also contains a [[The Hertz Corporation|Hertz]] rental car location, coffee shop, restaurant, a bike shop, offices, a museum, and loft condominiums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://streets.mn/2018/03/14/living-in-union-depot/|title=Living in Union Depot|last=Browender|first=Wolfie|date=2018-03-14|website=streets.mn|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Original Union Depot===\n{{Multiple image\n|align = left\n|direction = vertical\n|width = 200\n|image1 = Pf026545-1-.jpg\n|image2 = Saint Paul Union Depot.jpg\n|footer = The original depot before 1886 ''(top)'' and in 1890 ''(bottom)''\n}}\n\nThere have been two Union Depots in Saint Paul. The first was completed in 1881, and combined the services of several different railroads into one building (hence the \"union\"; see [[Union station]]). In 1888 the old station had its peak year, handling eight million passengers. That year, about 150 trains departed daily.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}} Around this time, the building was remodeled with a taller central tower and other alterations to the [[roof]]line.  This station burned in 1915.\n\n===Current building===\nThe current structure was started in 1917 but was not completed until 1923 because [[World War I]] caused construction to halt for several years.\n\nDuring its heyday, the depot hosted the passenger trains of nine railroads, and more than 20 million pieces of mail passed through the station to the neighboring St. Paul Central Downtown Post Office annually. At its peak in the 1920s, there were 282 train movements daily. The waiting room stood atop nine platforms serving 18 tracks; the eight northern ones closest to the headhouse were stub-end tracks, while the other ten ran through.  However, track ownership and trackage rights west of the station meant that most trains operated as though the station was a stub terminal. These trains, when they were intended to continue beyond the station, instead backed up to a wye just to the east to get to other main lines.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uniondepot.org/docs/2003%20LTK%20Depot%20Study/LTKFinalreport.pdf|title=Saint Paul Union Depot Analysis Final Report|accessdate=February 4, 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe Saint Paul Union Depot Company controlled {{convert|9.24|mi|km}} of St. Paul trackage and terminal facilities, including the depot building. The company was operated in tandem with the Minnesota Transfer Railway Company, with effective control of both properties exercised by the same board, composed of representatives of the nine tenants.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mnhs.org/library/findaids/00770.xml|title=Saint Paul Union Depot Company|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref>  \n\nTrain ridership began to erode in the 1920s as the automobile took hold and airlines began to operate.  The railroads sought ways stem the flow of passengers and compete with these new forms of transportation.  As the [[Great Depression]] unfolded, more aggressive moves were required.  The [[streamliner]] era in the United States began in 1934 with the introduction of the [[Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad|Chicago, Burlington and Quincy]]'s ''[[Pioneer Zephyr|Zephyr]]''.  After making a \"Dawn-to-Dusk Dash\" from [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]] to [[Denver, Colorado]], the CB&Q's interest soon turned to the Twin Cities run. A demonstration run was completed in 6 hours and 4 minutes, including six one-minute stops.<ref name=\"hiawatha\">{{Scribbins-Hiawatha-2007}}</ref> Other railroads were soon busy investigating how to run faster trains to Saint Paul and Minneapolis.\n[[Image:Locomotive William Crooks at St. Paul Union Depot 1954.jpg|thumb|left|William Crooks locomotive being set up as a static display in the station's waiting room in 1954. The engine remained on display there until 1975, when it was moved to the [[Lake Superior Railroad Museum]] in Duluth.]]\nThe first [[locomotive]] to run in [[Minnesota]], the ''[[William Crooks (locomotive)|William Crooks]]'', was displayed at the depot from 1955 until the station's 1971 closure, after which it was moved to the [[Lake Superior Railroad Museum]] in [[Duluth, Minnesota|Duluth]].\n\n===Early high-speed trains===\nOn January 2, 1935, high-speed express service to Chicago was introduced on the [[Chicago and North Western Railway]]'s ''[[Twin Cities 400|400]]'', cutting the scheduled time between the two cities from about 10 hours down to 7.  ''[[Time Magazine|Time]]'' dubbed the ''400'', \"the fastest train scheduled on the American Continent, fastest in all the world on a stretch over 200 mi.\"<ref name=\"time\">{{cite news|title=400|work=Time Magazine Archive|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,930785,00.html|accessdate=March 8, 2007|date=January 14, 1935}}</ref>  The C&NW beat two other railroads which had been planning 6\u00bd hour service to begin in the spring.  The [[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul & Pacific Railroad|Milwaukee Road]]'s ''[[Twin Cities Hiawatha|Hiawatha]]'' and the [[Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad|Burlington Route]]'s ''[[Twin Cities Zephyr]]'' were introduced with 6\u00bd hour service a few months later at the same time, and C&NW  matched their schedules.<ref name=\"hiawatha\"/><ref name=\"400-story\">{{Scribbins-400-2008}}</ref>\n\nThe Burlington ''Zephyrs'' were the first [[streamliner|streamlined]] [[diesel-electric locomotive|diesel-electric]] trains to serve the Twin Cities, and originally ran in an [[articulated car|articulated]] configuration.  The ''400'' (now renamed the ''Twin Cities 400'') followed in 1939, but using more conventional trucks and couplers to link passenger cars together.  The ''Hiawatha'' had always been powered by a streamlined (or, in the terminology of the Milwaukee Road, \"speedlined\") [[steam locomotive]].  The ''Twin Cities Zephyrs'' added a second set of trains daily in 1936, running the ''Morning Zephyr'' and ''Afternoon Zephyr'' from each terminal.  The ''Hiawatha'' added a second set of trains in 1939, and the ''Morning Hiawatha'' and ''Afternoon Hiawatha'' each provided daily service from Minneapolis-St. Paul and Chicago.\n\nThe ''Morning Hiawatha'' may have held the record as the world's [[land speed record for rail vehicles|fastest steam train]] on two or more measures: The {{convert|78.3|miles|km}} run from [[Sparta, Wisconsin|Sparta]] to [[Portage, Wisconsin]] was scheduled for 58 minutes&mdash;an average of {{convert|81|mph|km/h}}.  Speeds up to and above {{convert|100|mph|km/h}} were achieved on a daily basis, and the powerful [[Milwaukee Road class F7]] engines (designed for a \"reserve speed\" of {{convert|125|mph|km/h}}) likely ran more miles at or above {{convert|100|mph|km/h}} than any other steam locomotives in history.<ref>{{cite web|first=Bryan|last=Benn|url=http://www.germansteam.co.uk/FastestLoco/fastestloco.html#MR2|title=Fastest Steam Locomotive?|access-date=February 8, 2010|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060420181235/http://www.germansteam.co.uk/FastestLoco/fastestloco.html#MR2|archive-date=April 20, 2006|df=}}</ref>\n\nBurlington's diesel ''Zephyrs'' were also very fast, and they had to be\u2014the ''Zephyr'' route was about {{convert|20|mi|km}} longer than the competition.  In southwestern Wisconsin, a stretch of track between stations required an average speed of {{convert|84.4|mph|km/h}}.\n\nEventually, the ''Hiawathas'', ''Zephyrs'', and the ''400'' ran 6\u00bc-hour service between St. Paul and Chicago, and for a time the ''Morning Zephyr'' from Chicago reached St. Paul in six hours flat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://streamlinermemories.info/Zephyr/TwinZephyrsbro.pdf|title=Heritage from the Gods: Burlington\u2019s new 8 car Twin Zephyrs|publisher=[[Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad|Burlington Route]]|format=PDF|year=1937|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref>  In the 1950s, the federal government began imposing stricter rules for high-speed operation, and expensive advanced signaling was installed along the routes to the Twin Cities, though trains generally traveled a maximum of {{convert|90|to|100|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}. Unable to keep up with an increasing automobile speeds on an improving road network and other factors that kept passengers away from trains, train ridership declined and the five daily fast trains became unprofitable.\n\n===End of service===\nThe ''Twin Cities 400'' was the first victim, ending service on July 23, 1963.\n\nIt was announced that when [[Amtrak]] formally took over most passenger service on May 1, 1971, it would consolidate its Twin Cities service in Minneapolis at the [[Minneapolis Great Northern Depot]]. Accordingly, the Burlington (later [[Burlington Northern Railroad|Burlington Northern]]) ''Zephyrs'' ended service on April 30, 1971, the same day the depot closed.  The ''Afternoon Zephyr'' was the last train to serve the depot when it departed that evening bound for Minneapolis. At this time, this train was normally combined with the ''Empire Builder'' and ''North Coast Limited'' from Chicago to St. Paul, except on Fridays when it ran as a separate train. Since April 30 was a Friday, the ''Zephyr'' had the \"honor\" of being the last train to depart the station.<ref>Steve Glischinski, eyewitness account at depot on April 30, 1971.</ref>\n\n===Restoration and return of passenger service===\n[[File:Concourse of the Saint Paul Union Depot during renovation, 2011.jpg|thumb|left|Exterior of the station during renovation]]\nArea boosters had long hoped that trains would return to the Union Depot, and plans gathered steam as the [[Blue Line (Minnesota)|Blue Line]] [[light rail]] project in Minneapolis drew toward completion. Planners envisioned the depot being used for a restored Amtrak service along with Metro and Jefferson Lines buses.\n\nA few businesses had occupied the headhouse since the halt of train service in 1971, while the [[United States Postal Service]] (USPS) took over the rear of the building. The concourse and waiting room were used for some postal service activities and storage. After lying dormant for several years in the 1970s, the train tracks were removed from the train deck and it was paved with a flat surface. It began to be used for staging [[semi-trailer truck]]s carrying mail to and from the neighboring Downtown St. Paul Central Post Office as well as USPS employee parking. A driveway ramp was sliced into the train deck at the intersection of Kellogg Boulevard and Broadway Street for USPS vehicles. In the early 2000s, the upper levels of the headhouse were  converted into 33 2-story loft condominiums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stpaulcondos.com/project/union-depot-lofts/|title=Union Depot Lofts|website=StPaulCondos.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\n[[File:St Paul Union Depot Waiting Room Opening Day 3.jpg|thumb|left|Grand opening of the newly renovated waiting room]]\nIn 2005, the Ramsey County Regional Railroad Authority secured funding to renovate the station as an [[intermodal passenger transport|intermodal]] transit hub served by Amtrak trains, [[Metro Transit (Minnesota)|Metro Transit]] light rail, and intercity bus lines.<ref name=\"minnesota.publicradio.org\">{{cite news|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2012/12/08/regional/union-depot-reopening/|title=Party marks reopening of St. Paul's Union Depot|last=Shenoy|first=Rupa|website=minnesota.cbslocal.com|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=December 8, 2012|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"minnesota.cbslocal.com\">{{cite news|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2012/12/08/thousands-visit-st-pauls-newly-renovated-union-depot/|title=Thousands Visit St. Paul\u2019s Newly Renovated Union Depot|last=Melo|first=Frederick|website=minnesota.cbslocal.com|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=December 8, 2012|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"stpauluniondepot.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.stpauluniondepot.com/st-paul-depot-renovation/|title=Renovation|website=www.stpauluniondepot.com|access-date=May 10, 2014|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140512221408/http://www.stpauluniondepot.com/st-paul-depot-renovation/|archive-date=May 12, 2014|df=}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, the Ramsey County Board approved purchasing the depot headhouse for $8.2 million, to serve as a [[Green Line (Minnesota)|METRO Green Line]] [[light rail]] station and for future passenger rail use.<ref>{{cite web|title=St. Paul Union Depot purchase approved|url=http://www.railwayage.com//content/view/907/121/|work=[[Railway Age]]|date=June 4, 2009|accessdate=June 9, 2009}}</ref> In 2010, USPS moved most of the truck operations to a [[bulk mail]] processing center in [[Eagan, Minnesota]], making way for rehabilitation of the depot as a rail hub. Demolition of the Postal Service building that blocked track access to the station began in mid-March 2011. The USPS ramp cut all the way across the train deck and blocked the ability for tracks to be installed, so the ramp was modified during restoration to make a roughly right-angle turn to access new bus platforms on the north end of the train deck while freeing up room for a few tracks to be restored on the south end.\n\nThe renovation was completed in late November 2012 at a cost of $243 million, of which $35 million was provided by the US government through the [[Transportation Investment Generating Economic Recovery|TIGER]] program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.progressiverailroading.com/news/article/USDOT-approves-TIGER-grant-agreement-for-Minnesotas-Union-Depot--25091|title=USDOT approves TIGER grant agreement for Minnesota's Union Depot|website=www.progressiverailroading.com|publisher=Progressive Railroading|date=November 18, 2010|accessdate=November 20, 2010}}</ref> The renovated station re-opened to the public on December 8, 2012.<ref name=\"minnesota.publicradio.org\"/><ref name=\"minnesota.cbslocal.com\"/><ref name=\"stpauluniondepot.com\"/>\n\nThe first Amtrak train to service Saint Paul Union Depot was the westbound ''Empire Builder'' which stopped at the station at 11:30pm on May 7, 2014, 70 minutes late heading en route to [[Seattle]] and [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]. Officials welcomed the first passengers to depart the train at the depot.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/localnews/ci_25716518/amtraks-arrival-at-union-depot-celebrated/|title=After 43 years, St. Paul's Union Depot marks return of passenger trains|last=Melo|first=Fredrick|website=twincitiespress.com|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=May 7, 2014|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Special Events==\n[[File:Milwaukee Road 261 - North Pole Express.JPG|thumb|left|Milwaukee Road 261 decorated as the North Pole Express in 2014 at St. Paul Union Depot]]\nSince opening in late 2012,<ref name=\"minnesota.publicradio.org\"/> the Depot has hosted a number of events. On May 10, 2014 ([[National Train Day]]), the depot hosted [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] Historical Society's [[Great Northern 400|SD45 #400 (Hustle Muscle)]] from the [[Jackson Street Roundhouse]], as well as some historical equipment. Amtrak displayed three Superliner cars. There were several other displays around the Depot grounds.\n\nIn December 2014, for the first time in nearly 50 years, an active steam locomotive returned to St. Paul Union Depot. [[Milwaukee Road 261]] and some historic passenger cars, decorated as the \"North Pole Express\" ran short excursions to and from the depot. It was determined to be an overwhelming success, with intentions to operate the train again in 2015. While Milwaukee Road 261 was present, the Depot also got a visit from Canadian Pacific's traveling Holiday Train.\n\nOn May 9, 2015, the depot hosted National Train Day events once more, with [[Great Northern 400|GN SD45 #400]] from the Great Northern Railway Historical Society and Jackson Street Roundhouse, [[BNSF Railway]] sent a [[GE ES44C4]] to the event and pulled some of the Milwaukee Road 261 excursion cars that were also displayed there. Amtrak displayed a new [[Viewliner II]] baggage car that was about to begin service on the Empire Builder.\n\nOn December 9, 2017 Metro Transit and BNSF operated a Northstar Holiday Train between Big Lake and St. Paul Union Depot. Service was free of charge, and ridership was around 1,500. The event has become an annual tradition.\n\n===Union Depot Train Day===\nEvery year in May, the depot hosts a weekend of events named \"Train Day\" which showcases the history and future of railroad travel. Those in attendance are treated to model train layouts, exhibitors, tours and railroad equipment displays. This event replaced \"National Train Day\" after Amtrak disbanded the program after 2015.<ref>\nhttp://www.uniondepot.org/traindays/\n</ref>\n\nOn April 30 and May 1, 2016, the depot hosted a two-day event titled \"Union Depot Train Days\" to celebrate the building's 90th Anniversary. Various displays, vendors, and photographers were featured inside the depot. Outside featured numerous rail equipment, including [[Milwaukee Road 261]] under steam with 4 passenger cars, [[Amtrak Paint Schemes|Amtrak's Exhibit Train]], [[Twin Cities and Western Railroad]] locomotive, [[Great Northern 325]], a rare [[EMD SDP40]] and [[Northern Pacific]] RPO #1102 from the [[Minnesota Transportation Museum]], and [[Soo Line 2500|Soo Line FP7a #2500]].<ref>\nhttps://www.eventbrite.com/e/laker-rail-program-friday-night-photoshoot-tickets-20920727459#\n</ref>\n\nOn May 6, 2017, featured railroad equipment included Amtrak 42, the Veteran's locomotive, two [[Union Pacific]] locomotives, a TC&W locomotive and GN 325 and NP 1102. NP RPO #1102 had the distinction of being the \"Last Mail Train\" as Train Day attendees had mail transported inside the car from Union Depot to Osceola, Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eventbrite.com/e/33690886348?aff=efbneb|title=Railroad Photo Sessions - Union Depot St. Paul / Osceola|author=|date=|website=Eventbrite|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2018, [[Burlington Northern 6234]] and [[Soo Line 559]] were displayed along with Great Northern business car A-11, once an executive car for [[James J. Hill]]'s family, along with Union Pacific's [[Chicago & Northwestern]] 'heritage' locomotive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eventbrite.com/e/43320590051?aff=efbneb|title=LakerRail 2018|author=|date=|website=Eventbrite|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref> 2019 Train Days was held May 31-June 2 and featured [[Soo Line 700]] from Duluth and other unannounced equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eventbrite.com/e/59244488861?aff=efbneb|title=LakerRail 2019 Railroad Photography Show and Night Photo Session|author=|date=|website=Eventbrite|access-date=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Services==\n===Amtrak===\n[[File:Empire Builder at Union Depot (21751301612).jpg|thumb|left|Empire Builder at Union Depot]]\nServing this station is the ''[[Empire Builder]]'', named to honor Saint Paul-based mogul [[James J. Hill]] who constructed the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railroad]], and whose nickname was \"The Empire Builder\". Westbound trains head for [[Spokane, Washington]] and split there to serve both [[Seattle, Washington]] and [[Portland, Oregon]]; eastbound trains head for [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]]. \n\nThe ''Empire Builder'' originally stopped at the station from 1929 until 1971. In 1971, Amtrak consolidated all passenger rail service for the Twin Cities at the [[Minneapolis Great Northern Depot|Great Northern Station]] in [[Minneapolis]], and in 1978 moved to the [[Midway (Amtrak station)|Midway Station]] in Saint Paul, about halfway between the downtowns of the two cities.<ref name = Melo>{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/localnews/ci_25716518/amtraks-arrival-at-union-depot-celebrated|title=After 43 years, St. Paul's Union Depot marks return of passenger trains|last=Melo|first=Fredrick|website=twincitiespress.com|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date= May 7, 2014|access-date=May 10, 2014}}</ref> Service returned to the Union Depot from Midway in 2014 after it was delayed for almost two years from the depot's initial grand re-opening in 2012 due to negotiations with the owners of the railroads ([[Canadian Pacific Railway]], [[BNSF Railway]], and [[Union Pacific Railroad]]) in the area<ref name=\"Gilbert\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mprnews.org/story/2014/04/02/news/amtrak-union-depot|title=Amtrak sets May 7 return to St. Paul's Union Depot|last=Gilbert|first=Curtis|website=www.mprnews|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio|date=April 2, 2014|accessdate=May 2, 2014}}</ref> and the construction of new complex signals on the [[Merriam Park Subdivision]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.twincities.com/cityhallscoop/2013/01/14/amtraks-arrival-delayed-union-depot-welcomes-jefferson-bus-lines-whose-chair-now-runs-mndot/|title=Amtrak\u2019s arrival delayed. Union Depot welcomes Jefferson Bus Lines, whose chair now runs MnDOT. |website=twincites.com|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=January 14, 2013|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\nWestbound trains arrive from Chicago in the middle of the night, usually around 10:30&nbsp;p.m. Eastbound trains arrive from Seattle or Portland around breakfast time. Also included is an [[Amtrak Thruway Motorcoach]] to Duluth via Jefferson Lines. The station appears as '''St. Paul-Minneapolis''' in Amtrak timetables.\n\n===Light rail===\n[[File:Union Depot Light Rail Station in Saint Paul MN.jpg|thumb|left|Union Depot Light Rail Station]]\nThe depot serves as the [[METRO (Minnesota)|METRO]] [[Green Line (Minnesota)|Green Line]] light rail line's eastern terminus. The Green Line runs between St. Paul and Minneapolis with it's western terminus at [[Target Field station]] in the [[North Loop, Minneapolis|North Loop]] area of [[Downtown Minneapolis]]. The stop is in front of the headhouse, rather than at a platform under the waiting room. \n\nThe line opened on June 14, 2014. Utility relocation work in preparation for the Green Line began in front of the depot on 4th Street in August 2009, well before the line received final funding or approval.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2010/08/20/lowertown-light-rail-construction/|title=St. Paul's Lowertown dealing with light rail construction headaches|last=Yuen|first=Laura|website=minnesota.publicradio.com|publisher=Minnesota Public Radio|date=August 10, 2010|accessdate=September 10, 2010}}</ref> Track was laid from 2011\u20132012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Construction Update: Downtown St. Paul - Week of September 20, 2010|url=http://myemail.constantcontact.com/Project-Construction-Update---Downtown-St--Paul---Week-of-September-20--2010.html?soid=1102549393035&aid=8wuAWU1DAF8|website=myemail.constantcontact.com|publisher=Central Corridor Light Rail Transit|date=September 2010|accessdate=September 18, 2010}}</ref> While the Union Depot is the eastern terminus of service, the tracks continue beyond the station to the line's maintenance facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metrocouncil.org/transportation/ccorridor/construction/CCLRTConstructionScheduleAtAGlance.htm |title=Central Corridor LRT construction schedule at a glance |work=Central Corridor |publisher=Metropolitan Council |date=July 20, 2010 |access-date=September 18, 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924174951/http://www.metrocouncil.org/transportation/ccorridor/construction/CCLRTConstructionScheduleAtAGlance.htm |archive-date=September 24, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n===Intercity bus service===\n*[[Greyhound Lines]] arrived at Saint Paul Union Depot in March 2014 after initially pulling out of the project two years prior.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/localnews/ci_25312265/greyhound-coming-st-pauls-union-depot|title=Greyhound coming to St. Paul's Union Depot|last=Melo|first=Fredrick|website=twincitiespress.com|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=March 10, 2014|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref> Greyhound offers at least six coach bus departures a day and additional weekend service.\n*[[Jefferson Lines]] relocated from Midway Station to Saint Paul Union Depot in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2013/01/14/union-depot-welcomes-inner-city-bus-service/|title=Union Depot Welcomes Inner City Bus Service|website=minnesota.cbslocal.com|date=January 14, 2013|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Megabus (North America)|Megabus]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/localnews/ci_24978561/megabus-coming-st-pauls-union-depot?source=pkg|title=Megabus coming to St. Paul's Union Depot|last=Melo|first=Fredrick|website=twincitiespress.com|publisher=[[MediaNews Group]]|date=January 23, 2014|accessdate=May 10, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Local and regional bus service===\n*[[Metro Transit (Minnesota)|Metro Transit]]: 3, 16, 21, 54, 63, 70, 94, 262, 350, 351, 361, 364 and 417.\n*[[Minnesota Valley Transit Authority]]: 480, 484, 489.<ref name=\"route-changes-dec-2012\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metrotransit.org/Mobile/NewsItem.aspx?articleID=1175|title=These routes will change on Dec. 8|date=Dec 2012|work=Connect|publisher=[[Metro Transit (Minnesota)|Metro Transit]]|accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Planned services==\nThe current vision for the depot is to create a hub for intercity connections for [[Metro Transit (Minnesota)|local & regional bus service]], [[light rail]], and [[commuter rail]].\n\n===Light rail and bus rapid transit===\nBus rapid transit (BRT) has been selected for the [[Rush Line Corridor]] between St. Paul and [[White Bear Lake, Minnesota|White Bear Lake]]. The southern terminus of this route is planned to be at St. Paul Union Depot. The [[Gateway Corridor]] (now called the Gold Line) is also planned to be bus rapid transit and will operate between St. Paul and [[Woodbury, Minnesota|Woodbury]]. The [[Red Rock Corridor]] has also been proposed as a BRT service and eventually being upgraded to commuter rail, however plans are on hold as ridership on the current bus routes in this corridor are low.\n\nThe [[Riverview Corridor]] is planned to be a LRT/modern streetcar hybrid operating between St. Paul Union Depot and Mall of America. Riverview Corridor trains would share tracks and stations with the Metro Green Line between Central Station and Union Depot Station.\n\n===Regional rail===\nNumerous existing freight rail lines branch out from St. Paul Union Depot and could be upgraded and utilized by regional passenger trains. Currently MnDOT has studied regional rail from St. Paul Union Depot to [[Mankato]], [[Northfield, Minnesota|Northfield]], and Minneapolis (continuing further west as a through-service). In 2010, the [[Minnesota Department of Transportation]] also released a plan for regional rail stretching out from the Twin Cities to rural Minnesota and neighboring states, and at least some of the lines would run to Saint Paul.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dot.state.mn.us/planning/railplan/files/DraftSRPFinalReport.pdf|title=Minnesota Comprehensive Statewide Freight and Passenger Rail Plan (Draft Final Report)|date=December 2009|author=Cambridge Systematics, Inc., Kimley Horn and Associates, Inc., and TKDA, Inc.|publisher=[[Minnesota Department of Transportation]]|accessdate=February 8, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===High-speed rail===\nNew trains running at speeds above {{convert|100|mph|km/h}} to Chicago have also been discussed since at least 1991. The [[Midwest Regional Rail Initiative]] (MWRRI), led by the [[Wisconsin Department of Transportation]], has proposed a link to the Twin Cities running at up to {{convert|110|mph|abbr=on}}. The planned schedule time to Saint Paul would be just 5\u00bd hours.  Others including the French national railway [[SNCF]], which operates the [[TGV]] network, have proposed trains running at up to {{convert|220|mph|km/h}}.<ref name=\"sncf-midwest\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/sncf/Midwest.pdf|title=Midwest|date=September 14, 2009|publisher=SNCF|accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thetransportpolitic.com/2009/09/19/breaking-sncf-proposes-development-of-high-speed-rail-in-midwest-texas-florida-and-california-corridors/|title=SNCF Proposes Development of High-Speed Rail in Midwest, Texas, Florida, and California Corridors|last=Freemark|first=Yonah|work=The Transport Politic|date=September 19, 2009|accessdate=December 6, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Local significance==\n{{multiple image\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width     = 250\n| image1    = Saint Paul Union Depot Frieze.jpg\n| caption1  = \n| image2    = St Paul Union Depot Waiting Room Steam Locomotive Frieze.jpg\n| caption2  = [[Frieze]] detailing on the waiting room walls\n}}\nPrior to the station's reopening in December 2012, Josh Collins, a spokesperson for Ramsey County Regional Rail Authority, referred to the potential of the station to be \"the living room of Saint Paul.\"<ref name=\"Duchschere new day\">{{cite news|last=Duchschere|first=Kevin|title=A new day is coming for St. Paul's Union Depot|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/stpaul/182112301.html?page=all&prepage=1&c=y&refer=y|accessdate=December 5, 2012|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=December 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Architecture===\nThe entrance to Union Depot, the [[headhouse]], is considered a somewhat severe example of [[neoclassicism|neoclassical]] [[architecture]], with a robust aesthetic.  A series of tall Doric columns line the front fa\u00e7ade.  The [[concourse]] and the waiting room that extends out to the platforms, where trains once rolled in, is considered to be one of the great architectural achievements in the city.  The building was designed by Charles Frost.<ref name=\"Duchschere new day\"/>\n\nThe waiting room is flooded with natural light from skylights.  These skylights were blackened during the [[Second World War]], but restored for the 2012 re-opening.<ref name=\"Duchschere new day\"/>\n\nThe building was added to the [[National Register of Historic Places]]<ref name=\"Duchschere new day\"/> in 1974.\n\nThe restoration and new addition were designed by [[Hammel, Green and Abrahamson]] Architects & Engineers (HGA).\n\n===Railway mapping===\nMilepost for rail lines that originated in Saint Paul, such as the Great Northern and Northern Pacific, had used the depot as milepost 0. This is still evident in timetables and mileposts used by the BNSF Railway<ref>BNSF Twin Cities Division Timetable No. 2. November 17, 2004. Note: The [[Midway Subdivision]] and [[St. Paul Subdivision]] both begin at Seventh Street junction. The [[Staples Subdivision]] (ex combined GN and NP) and [[Wayzata Subdivision]] (ex GN) continue the numbering.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n===Other notable trains to serve the depot===\n*''[[Twin Star Rocket]]''\n*''[[Gopher (train)|Gopher]]'' and ''Badger''\n*''[[North Coast Limited]]''\n*''[[Western Star (train)|Western Star]]''\n\n===Other rail stations in the Twin Cities===\n*[[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Depot Freight House and Train Shed]] - Minneapolis destination for [[Milwaukee Road]], [[Minneapolis, St. Paul and Sault Ste. Marie Railroad|Soo Line]], and [[Rock Island Railroad]] passenger trains; now converted to other uses\n*The [[Minneapolis Great Northern Depot]] in Minneapolis was used by trains of the [[Chicago and North Western Railway]], [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]], and [[Northern Pacific]] railroads\n*The [[Chicago Great Western Railway]] had a station on south Washington Avenue in Minneapolis\n*The [[Minneapolis and St. Louis Railway]] had a station on north 5th Street in Minneapolis\n* [[Midway (Amtrak station)|Midway Station]] - former Amtrak station\n* [[Target Field Station (Metro Transit station)|Target Field Station]] - terminus for the [[Northstar Line]] commuter trains\n\n===Regional and enhanced-speed train proposals===\n*[[Chicago Hub Network]]\n*[[Passenger rail projects in Minnesota]]\n\n===Other initially abandoned stations===\n* [[Kansas City Union Station]] - An Amtrak station that was abandoned in 1985 but restored in 2002\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/twincities/stories/2009/12/07/daily40.html|title=Mortenson team picked for $150M St. Paul Union Depot transit hub|last=Black|first=Sam|date=December 10, 2009|work=Minneapolis / St. Paul Business Journal  |accessdate=December 16, 2009}}\n*Diers, John (1913). ''St. Paul Union Depot''. Minneapolis: [[University of Minnesota Press]]. {{ISBN|978 0 8166 5610 3}}\n*Mack, Doug. (August 11, 2004). [https://web.archive.org/web/20050801075245/http://www.professoryeti.com/20040811/features-station.php Goodbye Mail, Hello Rail.]  Professor Yeti.  Retrieved June 12, 2005.\n*{{cite news|url=http://www.twincities.com/mld/pioneerpress/news/local/11831172.htm|title=Post 