 [[Bratislava]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Slovenia}}\n** [[Ljubljana]] (Embassy)\n*{{ESP}}\n** [[Madrid]] (Embassy)\n** [[Barcelona]] (Consulate-General)\n** [[Palma de Mallorca]]  (Consulate)\n** [[Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]] (Consulate)\n** [[M\u00e1laga]] (Consulate-General)\n*{{SWE}}\n** [[Stockholm]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Switzerland}}\n** [[Bern]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Ukraine}}\n** [[Kiev]] (Embassy)\n*{{GBR}}\n** [[London]] ([[Embassy of Germany, London|Embassy]])\n** [[Edinburgh]] (Consulate-General)\n\n==Oceania==\n*{{AUS}}\n** [[Canberra]] (Embassy)\n** [[Sydney]] (Consulate-General)\n*{{NZL}}\n** [[Wellington]] (Embassy)\n\n==Multilateral organisations==\n* [[Brussels]] (Permanent Mission to the {{flag|European Union}} and {{flag|NATO}})\n* [[Geneva]] (Permanent Mission to the {{flag|United Nations}} and other international organisations)\n* [[New York City|New York]] (Permanent Mission to the {{flag|United Nations}})\n* [[Paris]] (Permanent Mission to the [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] and {{flag|UNESCO}})\n* [[Strasbourg]] (Permanent Mission to the {{flag|Council of Europe}})\n* [[Vienna]] (Permanent Mission to the [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]])\n\n==Countries without German diplomatic mission==\n\nCurrently, there are no German diplomatic missions (but in some cases honorary consuls) in\n\nAndorra, Antigua and Barbuda, Bahamas, Barbados, Belize, Bhutan, Cape Verde, Central African Republic, Cook Islands, Comores, Dominica, East Timor, Eswatini, Fiji, The Gambia, Grenada, Guinea-Bissau, Guyana, Kiribati, Lesotho, Liechtenstein, Maldives, Marshall Islands, Micronesia, Monaco, Nauru, Niue, Palau, Papua New Guinea, Solomon Islands, Samoa, San Marino, S\u00e3o Tom\u00e9 and Pr\u00edncipe, Seychelles, Somalia, St. Kitts and Nevis, St. Lucia, St. Vincent and the Grenadines, Suriname, Syria, Tonga, Tuvalu, and Vanuatu. \n\nWhen in a non-EU country where there is no German embassy, German citizens as EU citizens have the right to get consular protection from '''the embassy of any other EU country present in that country.'''\n\n==Travel warnings and \"''Krisenvorsorgeliste''\"==\nGermany regularly publishes '''travel warnings''' on the website of the [[Ausw\u00e4rtiges Amt]] (Federal Foreign Office) to its citizens. The Office allows German citizens to register online in a special list, the '''Krisenvorsorgeliste''' (\"Crisis-Prevention List\") before they travel abroad (''Elektronische Erfassung von Deutschen im Ausland [ELEFAND]'' Electronic Registration of Germans Being Abroad). With a password, the registered persons can change or update their data. The registration is '''voluntary''' and '''free of charge.''' It can be used for longer stays (longer than 6 months), but also for a '''vacation of only two weeks.''' The earliest date of registration is '''10 days before the planned trip.'''\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[Foreign relations of Germany]]\n* {{section link|List of German consuls in Jerusalem, Jaffa, Haifa and Eilat|List of consuls in Eilat}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Embassies of Germany}}\n{{commons category|Consulates of Germany}}\n* [http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/diplo/en/Laenderinformationen/02-WebseitenAV/Uebersicht.html Foreign Office of the Federal Republic of Germany]\n* [https://australien.diplo.de/au-en/embassy-consulates/botschaft German Embassy in Canberra, Australia]\n* [http://www.buenos-aires.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Buenos Aires, Argentina]\n* [http://www.ottawa.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Ottawa, Canada]\n* [http://www.peking.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Beijing, China]\n* [http://www.paris.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Paris, France]\n* [http://www.madrid.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Madrid, Spain]\n* [http://www.bern.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Bern, Switzerland]\n* [http://www.wellington.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Wellington, New Zealand]\n* [http://www.oslo.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Oslo, Norway]\n* [http://www.london.diplo.de/ German Embassy in London, United Kingdom]\n* [http://www.germany.info/ German Embassy in Washington D.C., United States]\n* [http://www.abu-dhabi.diplo.de/Vertretung/abudhabi/en/Startseite.html/ German Embassy in Abu Dhabi, United Arab Emirates]\n* [http://www.dubai.diplo.de/Vertretung/dubai/en/Startseite.html/ German Consulate-General in Dubai, United Arab Emirates]\n* [http://www.caracas.diplo.de/ German Embassy in Caracas, Venezuela]\n\n{{Europe topic|List of diplomatic missions of|UK_only=yes|countries_only=yes}}\n{{German diplomatic missions}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Diplomatic Missions Of Germany}}\n[[Category:Diplomatic missions of Germany| ]]\n[[Category:Germany diplomacy-related lists|Diplomatic missions]]\n[[Category:Lists of diplomatic missions by sending country|Germany]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n[[Image:Diplomatic missions of Germany.png|thumb|right|400px|Diplomatic missions of Germany]]\nThis is a '''list of diplomatic missions of Germany'''. Historically, the German state of [[Prussia]] and several smaller German states had sent emissaries abroad prior to the establishment of the [[North German Confederation]], the precursor to the modern [[Germany|Federal Republic of Germany]].\n\nIn 1874, Germany had only four embassies (in [[London]], [[Paris]], [[Saint Petersburg]], and [[Vienna]]), but this was complemented by non-ambassadorial representation in the form of 14 ministerial posts (in [[Athens]], [[Bern]], [[Brussels]], [[The Hague]], [[Constantinople]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Lisbon]], [[Madrid]], [[Rome]], [[Stockholm]], [[Peking]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Washington, D.C.]], and to the [[Holy See]]), seven consulates-general with diplomatic status (in [[Alexandria]], [[Belgrade]], [[Bucharest]], [[London]], [[New York City|New York]], [[Budapest]], and [[Warsaw]]), and 37 consulates and vice-consulates headed by consular officers. By 1914, five additional embassies were established in [[Constantinople]], [[Madrid]], [[Rome]], [[Washington, D.C.]], and [[Tokyo]]. The Foreign Office progressively reformed itself at this time to serve Germany's rising commercial and colonial interests abroad, as well as to reflect the professionalization of [[diplomacy]] generally.\n\nPolitics of the [[Third Reich]] affected the Foreign Office. In 1935 the [[Reich Citizenship Law|Reich Citizenship Act]] led to the forced retirement of over 120 tenured civil servants. Positions and structures were created to imbed [[NSDAP]] representatives, and the [[SS]] began to be posted abroad as \"police attach\u00e9s\". Under [[Joachim von Ribbentrop]] the Reich Foreign Ministry grew from 2,665 officers in 1938 to a peak of 6,458 in 1943, despite missions abroad closing as a consequence of the [[Second World War]].\n\nGermany's post-war diplomatic network started as early as 1949 with a mission in [[Paris]] to the newly formed [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]]. The following year consulates-general were (re)opened in [[London]], [[New York City]], [[Paris]], [[Istanbul]], [[Amsterdam]], [[Brussels]], [[Rome]], and [[Athens]] (until 1951 these were not embassies, as by virtue of the Occupation Statute the three allied powers had competence of foreign affairs; these consulates were intended to just manage commercial and consular affairs).  [[West Germany]]'s [[Foreign Office (Germany)|Federal Foreign Office]] grew, and by the time of Germany's reunification in 1990, there were 214 diplomatic missions abroad. Following [[German reunification]], the Federal Republic inherited several diplomatic representations of the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (East Germany)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]] of former [[East Germany]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/diplo/en/AAmt/Geschichte/GeschichteAApdf.pdf|title=The History of the German Foreign Office|first=Ludwig|last=Biewer|website=auswaertiges-amt.de|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060621165456/https://www.auswaertiges-amt.de/diplo/en/AAmt/Geschichte/GeschichteAApdf.pdf|archive-date=21 June 2006|url-status=dead|access-date=29 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe West German embassy in [[Stockholm]] was [[West German embassy siege|occupied]] by the [[Red Army Faction]] in 1975. In 1989 its embassies in [[Embassy of Germany in Budapest|Budapest]] and [[Embassy of Germany in Prague|Prague]] sheltered fleeing East Germans while waiting for permission to travel onwards to West Germany; permission was subsequently given by the Czechoslovakian and Hungarian governments, accelerating the collapse of socialist hegemony in Eastern Europe. \n\nGermany \"assists\" [[Sweden]] in its duties as protecting power for several Western states in [[North Korea]] \"when necessary\".\n\nToday Germany manages 226 diplomatic missions abroad (listed below). There are also 354 unpaid honorary consuls.\n\n==Africa==\n[[File:German Embassy, central Baghdad, Iraq.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Baghdad]]\n[[Image:Nesterov pal\u00e1c 1.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Bratislava]]\n[[Image:German Embassy in Canberra.jpg|right|thumb|[[Embassy of Germany in Canberra]]]]\n[[File:German embassy den haag2010.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in The Hague]]\n[[File:Embassy of Germany in Kyiv 2.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Kiev]]\n[[File:Nemsko veleposlanistvo v Ljubljani german embassy ljubljana Slovenia.jpg|thumb|German Embassy in [[Ljubljana]]]]\n[[File:DtBotschaftGB.jpg|thumb|right|[[German Embassy in London]]]]\n[[File:Deutsche Botschaft in Madrid (Spanien) 01.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Madrid]]\n[[File:Embajada de Alemania en la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico.jpg|thumb|right|Embassy of Germany in Mexico City]]\n[[File:German Embassy Mosfilmovskaya Street.jpg|thumb|[[Embassy of Germany in Moscow]]]]\n[[File:General Consulate of Germany.jpg|thumb|right|German Consulate-General in Saint Petersburg]]\n[[File:Oscars gate 45 - 2009-06-20 at 17-30-55.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Oslo]]\n[[Image:German Embassy Ottawa.jpg|thumb|right|[[Embassy of Germany in Ottawa|German Embassy in Ottawa]]]]\n[[File:BritishHC PortofSpain.jpg|thumb|German Embassy in [[Port of Spain]]]]\n[[Image:German Embassy in Prague.jpg|thumb|right|[[Embassy of Germany in Prague]]]]\n[[File:German Embassy in Pyongyang, DPRK.JPG|thumb|right|German Embassy in Pyongyang]]\n[[File:Botschaft Tokyo.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Tokyo]]\n[[Image:DeUkEmbassyRkv.JPG|thumb|right|Building of the German and the British Embassy in Reykjav\u00edk]]\n[[Image:Riga DeutscheBotschaft.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Riga]]\n[[File:Tysklands ambassad 2008.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Stockholm]]\n[[File:Embassy of Germany to Estonia in Tallinn.jpg|thumb|right|Embassy of Germany in Tallinn]]\n[[Image:Deutsche Botschaft Wien.jpg|thumb|German Embassy in Vienna]]\n[[Image:Embassy of Germany in Warsaw.jpg|thumb|right|German Embassy in Warsaw]]\n[[Image:Embassy of Germany, Washington.jpg|thumb|right|[[German Embassy in Washington, D.C.]]]]\n[[File:NYC German consulate.jpg|thumb|German Consulate-General and Permanent Mission to the United Nations in New York]]\n[[File:German Consulate General in San Francisco.jpg|thumb|right|Consulate-General of Germany in San Francisco]]\n[[Image:WellingtonEmbassy-Germany.jpg|thumb|right|[[Embassy of Germany in Wellington]]]]\n[[File:Embassy of Germany in Yerevan.JPG|thumb|right|German Embassy in Yerevan]]\n*{{Flag|Algeria}}\n** [[Algiers]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Angola}}\n** [[Luanda]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Benin}}\n** [[Cotonou]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Botswana}}\n** [[Gaborone]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Burkina Faso}}\n** [[Ouagadougou]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Burundi}}\n** [[Bujumbura]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Cameroon}}\n** [[Yaound\u00e9]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Chad}}\n** [[N'Djamena]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Democratic Republic of the Congo}}\n** [[Kinshasa]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Republic of the Congo}}\n** [[Brazzaville]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Djibouti}}\n** [[Djibouti City]] (Embassy)\n*{{EGY}}\n** [[Cairo]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Equatorial Guinea}}\n** [[Malabo]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Eritrea}}\n** [[Asmara]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Ethiopia}}\n** [[Addis Ababa]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Gabon}}\n** [[Libreville]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Ghana}}\n** [[Accra]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Guinea}}\n** [[Conakry]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Ivory Coast}}\n** [[Abidjan]] (Embassy)\n*{{KEN}}\n** [[Nairobi]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Liberia}}\n** [[Monrovia]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Madagascar}}\n** [[Antananarivo]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Malawi}}\n** [[Lilongwe]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Mali}}\n** [[Bamako]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Mauritania}}\n** [[Nouakchott]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Morocco}}\n** [[Rabat]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Mozambique}}\n** [[Maputo]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Namibia}}\n** [[Windhoek]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Niger}}\n** [[Niamey]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Nigeria}}\n** [[Abuja]] (Embassy)\n** [[Lagos]] (Consulate-General)\n*{{Flag|Rwanda}}\n** [[Kigali]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Senegal}}\n** [[Dakar]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Sierra Leone}}\n** [[Freetown]] (Embassy)\n*{{ZAF}}\n** [[Pretoria]] (Embassy)\n** [[Cape Town]] (Consulate-General)\n*{{SSD}}\n** [[Juba]] (Embassy)\n*{{SDN}}\n** [[Khartoum]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Tanzania}}\n** [[Dar es Salaam]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Togo}}\n** [[Lom\u00e9]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Tunisia}}\n** [[Tunis]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Uganda}}\n** [[Kampala]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Zambia}}\n** [[Lusaka]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Zimbabwe}}\n** [[Harare]] (Embassy)\n\n==Americas==\n*{{Flag|Argentina}}\n** [[Buenos Aires]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Bolivia}}\n** [[La Paz]] (Embassy)\n*{{Flag|Brazil}}\n** [[Bras\u00edlia]] (Embassy)\n** [[Porto Alegre]] (Consulate-General)\n** [[Recife]] (Consulate-General)\n** [[Rio de Janeiro]] (Consulate-General)\n** [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] (Consulate-General)\n*{{CAN}}\n** [[Ottawa]] ([[German Embassy, Ottawa|Embassy]])\n** [[Montreal]] (Consulate-General)\n** [[Toronto]] (Consulate-General)\n** [[Vancouver]] ([[Canada Place|Consulate-General]])\n*{{Flag|Chile}}\n*